These wealth, however, brings one calamity to the popes, guaranteeing that the powerful armed forces of Indonesia retain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by The New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local soldiers and units almost $20 million, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands of greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden dwelling and are relentlessly suppressed.
Human rights defenders have claimed that since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military forces and thousands have been raped, tortured and deprived of their liberty.
