Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, 16 - year - old Julianus Amo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government building of the electoral commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered in the soccer field in front of the local police station and military command centre to demand justice.
They brought with them the ritual hunting bows and filled the watts, the dance of the Papuan tribe of Mee pago, running round and playing birds' singing.
Some protestors began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation got worse, internal radio soldiers were ordered: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them”, he said, according to an official document that saw “TIME” correspondents, but which was not published in local media.
The 50 - year - old Jeremiah Kaiame, head of the Kego Koto area in Enarotali, felt danger approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to leave the house.
No one wanted to listen to him.
