There is now a new type of staff start-up that helps companies to find out how their staff feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure staff involvement, they allow companies to conduct express interviews, contact certain teams and demographic groups, offer anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow informants to bypass top management and address the Directorate directly.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup from Redwood City, whose analytical programmes are used by companies to measure staff involvement.
Errett said that she had reached a greater understanding of what her staff thought and felt in three years of using Glint.
In addition to express requests and questionnaires of certain commands, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in an illustrative form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low rating of approval, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are well aware that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber, who was involved in a scandal when a former employee published a post on a blog that described the aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, it's a desire to control the situation, an opportunity for a profitable business.
The Internet portal “Let’s talk about payment”, dedicated to financial technologies, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry can cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Convercent launch from Denver, Colorado, to help companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year in the face of the downfall of Ubera's reputation.
The Convergence has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among the clients.
Like “Glint”, “Convercent” allows companies to send personal interviews of staff, collect confidential responses in real-time, and view heat maps of problem zones.
It also provides a hot line for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go straight to the director's office.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors”, said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Konvercent.
If it is found that the company is ill-treated or unethical, even if the inspector is not intervened, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by clients, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 facilities, has been using Konvercent for over a year to make sure that employees are aware of the rules and procedures, and to offer a simple way to contact the company's head office.
Earlier, if the staff member wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for the telephone number or e-mail address of the head office, file an official complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, the head of the legal office of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to track staff complaints.
Now that the company is using the Konvercent service, the problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, prejudice and unfair pay — can be found and dealt with more quickly.
“I can get closer to a comprehensive, comprehensive understanding of the situation of staff”, said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“And we protect our shareholders from trials with staff.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values and involvement of employees more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen, an accountant, suffered a breakdown due to ethical violations resulting from Enron.
But only when “social networks became widespread” did companies realize that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution online.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy”, he said.
Both “Glint” and “Convercent” offer their software as a service, taking regular fees from companies for the use of their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity approved by venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, Konvercent received $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, resulting in total company capital of $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising, given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today ' s staff expect more from their jobs than was previously the case.
In highly competitive markets, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, only the necessary minimum.
The staff want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in companies, they feel that they are hearing them, and that the work they are doing is the result, they are more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, Vice President for Global Benefits and Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Converter and Glint are used.
Investors receive income when business from their portfolio goes well; business goes well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the commitment and involvement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to workplace culture experts, it is important to have data on staff involvement.
But the data is useless until the company's guardians take action.
In fact, if the company asks staff for feedback, it may give the impression that changes are coming.
And if change does not occur quickly enough or not at all, frustration may develop, and staff will lose interest.
“If you are going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you must be prepared to hold 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Ratt, president of Kotter International management firm, who had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you do not go to the end, the staff will say, ‘Did you really hear me?
You don't care?
If you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly staff interviews, is able to take action the same day that someone reports the problem with Glint.
And after collecting feedback from staff members who were unhappy with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is getting new knowledge of its staff and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help her to keep staff in a sector known for its high turnover.
"If you are not trying to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
