Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help facilitate KPC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your food tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve the symptoms of intestinal inflammatory diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects some 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, leads to cola and exhalation of the abdomen, chronic or bloody pride, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acids of triptphane protein contribute to the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestines are ensuring that harmful microbes from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of initiating an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protect the body, and do not harm sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severely impaired towards inflammation, this may lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice with certain bacteria in their intestines have an increased tolerance for cells.
And this bacteria needs triptphane, one of the building blocks of a protein, to trigger the emergence of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a single type of bacteria called Lactobacillus routeri, which is part of a normal gut microbioma, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptphane was contained in mouse nutrition, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. routers and a rich tryptophan diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflamed environment in the intestine.
Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganas, studying the variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line, but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the microbiomy of the intestines of the mice — the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinal cells of the mice was sequenced and six types of bacteria were found in the mice with immune cells but not in the mice without them.
The mice grown in a sterile environment that had no good microbioma and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. routers, and the immune cells appeared to them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. routers in a liquid environment and then carried small amounts of fluid — without bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells released from mice.
Immune cells have become more tolerant cells.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it was a by-product of triptophane processing known as indol-3-milk acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of triptphane in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 per cent, but when the level of triptphane was halved, the number of cells also dropped twice.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have the same tolerance for cells as mice, and most of us have L. routers in their gastric tract.
