The White House prop cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
According to the records of the armed forces provided to Time magazine, the White House decision last month to send a helicopter to the South Lawn for an event devoted to American industrial production cost taxpayers a total of $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as “Marine One”, when the president is on board, became the central element of the event held in the White House on 17 July that demonstrated American construction programmes.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pens and White House officials reviewed technology products from all 50 states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut was displayed near a yacht from the state of Man, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and an airlift from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Aircraft (HMX-1), the Helicopter Control Unit, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or a “FRAGO”, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to know that you are aware because this is an unusual press event,” wrote HMX-1 commander in an e-mail to his superior, the first Deputy Chief of Aviation of the Marine Corps, on the e-mail before the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the working hours limits.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the operation, while the unit security officers stayed close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the recordings received by Time magazine whether the second crew was required.
The Hetch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the measure was contrary to that decision.
“Besides, we asked if it was a violation of the Hetch law and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“You don’t seem to have anything to do with it,” the deputy chief replied.
The “Done in America” event was declared an official event by the White House and was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health reform that was then in the Senate and commended the attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking them is only for the sake of photo opportunity.
Trump had already been the subject of discussions in February, when the Presidential plane had flown backwards during its first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account had been filled with complaints about the use of a presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled to see the “Made in America” display of products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” said White House press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around Washington Agglomeration and the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to the White House with accuracy to an inch.
When Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight carried out for the “Made in America” event was credited to the crew for the required training flights per month.
The unit ' s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Ministry of Defence's 2017 fiscal year, the rate of reimbursement of the Ministry of Defence for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The records of the unit indicate that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes to each side of its airport based on the flight base of the Quantico Marine Corps in Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using the helicopter is well below that rate.
“It is wrong to calculate the cost for taxpayers, based on an approximate rate of reimbursement”, says Walters.
“These indicative rates include the composition, servicing and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriation”.
According to a study carried out in 2015 by the REND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do indeed take into account the fuel, services and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House press secretary, Sean Spicer, spoke in defence of the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to show off this week the things done in America,” said Spicer.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that's worked tirelessly to create so many Americans.
It is therefore appropriate to draw this attention.”
It was not clear whether Trump was interacting with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely in the driver’s seat in the fire car.
Inside the White House, Trump approached representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products of the company.
"I know Sikorsky well," the president said. "I have three of them."
